<br>
Actually, I think it's the opposite.  In EQ, dying has zero experience penalty with resurrection.  In DAOC, there's always an experience penalty.  Dying means so little in EQ in the high end game that it becomes an integral gameplay technique for some players in high-end encounters.<br>
<br>
Broomhilda says:  <b><i> often wondered why OSI(UO) never specialized their servers in the manner your speaking about. There was definitely a clash between differing playing styles. I remember specializing the servers was brought up to them, dunno why they didnt do it.</b></i><br>
<br>
They did -- look at Siege Perilous, a sort of hardcore server.<br>
<br>
Still, I doubt they could do it in EQ as Sorrun suggests.  Powergamers feed not so much on the types items or levels, but on the power differential between them and the "lesser" gamers.  If a "light" server were to open up for casual players, many powergamers would swarm to it just to be better than everyone else.<br>
<br>
Also, since the content across servers must be somewhat uniform, I can imagine many high level guilds doing high level encounter reconnaissance on this server, like trying to kill the bosses just to hone their strategy for the "real" servers.<br>
<br>
<b><i>Actually, what should happen is Verant should do content</b></i><br>
<br>
...not including camp/sitting-on-your-butt-doing-nothing times, I hope. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaurincotg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saurin CoTG</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/14/01 6:12:44 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> No doubt about it, on the content comparison EQ blows Camelot away.  In many respects folks will say it is unfair to compare a game that is two months old with one that is 3 years old, but in a marketplace things are not always fair.  <br>
<br>
This thread has touched on my two biggest issues with both of these games.  <br>
<br>
Camelot--content<br>
<br>
EQ--time investment<br>
<br>
<br>
The difference for me is, Mythic will eventually add the content to its game, while Verant will never significantly reduce the time investment required for EQ. <br>
<br>
On the slightly off topic thougth of the day.  Anyone else find it odd that after leveling a character to 60 that they apparently have acknowledged is unbalanced in one way or the other, you now have to invest additional experience to acquire abilities to balance you?  (most of the alternative advancement abilities I see came from the class balancing lists done oh so long ago)  Oh well, I could be wrong :-)<br>
